"title": "5672: concubines",
"media_type": "Text",
"index_reference": "5672: concubines",
"language": "eng",
"review_level": "None",
"content": "<p>A woman, often a servant or slave, with whom a man had regular sexual relations, but to whom he was not married. A concubine did not have the rights of a wife and her children were not rightful heirs, though a wife might offer a servant to her husband as a concubine to have children on her behalf.</p>\n<h2>Concubines and wives</h2>\n<h3>Concubines were distinguished from wives</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Kgs11:3\">1KI 11:3</a></strong> <em>Having concubines alongside wives was accepted in a polygamous society.</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Judg8:30-Judg8:31\">JDG 8:30–8:31</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Sam5:13\">2SA 5:13</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Sam19:5\">2SA 19:5</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Chr11:21\">2CH 11:21</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Dan5:2-Dan5:3\">DAN 5:2–5:3</a></p>\n<h3>Concubines were sometimes called wives</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen16:3\">GEN 16:3</a></strong> <em>Hagar was Abraham's “wife” only in a secondary sense.</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen25:1\">GEN 25:1</a> <em>Keturah was one of Abraham's concubines</em>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Judg19:1-Judg19:4\">JDG 19:1–19:4</a></p>\n<h3>Concubines did not have the rights of a wife</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen21:8-Gen21:14\">GEN 21:8–21:14</a> <em>They were more easily dismissed</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod21:7-Exod21:11\">EXO 21:7–21:11</a> <em>They did have some legal protection.</em></p>\n<h3>Maidservants were given as concubines</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen30:3-Gen30:6\">GEN 30:3–30:6</a></strong> <em>Bilhah's sons would be regarded by Rachel as her own and would thus share the inheritance with Jacob's other sons.</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen30:9\">GEN 30:9</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen16:1-Gen16:2\">GEN 16:1–16:2</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gal4:22-Gal4:23\">GAL 4:22–4:23</a></p>\n<h3>The tension between concubines and wives</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen16:4-Gen16:6\">GEN 16:4–16:6</a></strong> <em>Though Abraham's concubine, Hagar's status was still that of servant.</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen21:9\">GEN 21:9</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Prov30:23\">PRO 30:23</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gal4:29\">GAL 4:29</a></p>\n<h3>Children born to concubines were not rightful heirs</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen21:10-Gen21:12\">GEN 21:10–21:12</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen25:5-Gen25:6\">GEN 25:5–25:6</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Judg9:18\">JDG 9:18</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rom9:7\">ROM 9:7</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gal4:30\">GAL 4:30</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Heb11:18\">HEB 11:18</a></p>\n<h2>Concubines were a symbol of possession</h2>\n<h3>By taking Jacob's concubine, Reuben laid premature claim to his father's estate</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen35:22\">GEN 35:22</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen49:3-Gen49:4\">GEN 49:3–49:4</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Chr5:1\">1CH 5:1</a></p>\n<h3>Taking the concubine(s) of a king was tantamount to laying claim to the kingdom</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Sam3:7\">2SA 3:7</a></strong> <em>Abner is accused here of trying to usurp Ish-Bosheth's inheritance.</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Sam12:8\">2SA 12:8</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Sam16:21-2Sam16:22\">2SA 16:21–16:22</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Kgs2:21-1Kgs2:22\">1KI 2:21–2:22</a></p>\n<h2>Further examples of concubines</h2>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen22:23-Gen22:24\">GEN 22:23–22:24</a> <em>Nahor's concubine, Reumah</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen36:12\">GEN 36:12</a> <em>Eliphaz' concubine, Timna</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Judg19:1\">JDG 19:1</a> <em>a Levite's concubine</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Sam15:16\">2SA 15:16</a> <em>David's concubines</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Chr1:32\">1CH 1:32</a> <em>Abraham's concubine, Keturah</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Chr2:46-1Chr2:48\">1CH 2:46–2:48</a> <em>Caleb's concubines, Ephah and Maacah</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Chr7:14\">1CH 7:14</a> <em>Manasseh's concubine</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Esth2:14\">EST 2:14</a> <em>Xerxes' concubines</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Dan5:23\">DAN 5:23</a> <em>Belshazzar's concubines</em></p>",
